On Wed, 24 Apr 2024 at 14:02, David Clements <dclements1@ahs.pmat.academy<mailto:dclements1@ahs.pmat.academy>> wrote:
Hello All

I'll do my best to clarify the problems that exist with the M1 music computers. All of the issues have been highlighted for some time (over two years) right back to when Kevin was out IT tech in school. Unfortunately the lack of a consistent tech has not helped, but Rachid is aware of them and seeking solutions.

PROBLEM 1

There is a problem with some Macs connecting to the network on the far wall in particular. Both Holly and now Rachid have highlighted the problem could be with the old network switches they are connected to.

Solution: test and potentially upgrade the switches for L40 and test the individual connections.

PROBLEM 2

Password reset. The Macs seem to request user password changes much more often than other computers in school. On top of this there seems to be some synchronization issues when changing.

Change the password reset settings potentially avoiding requests on the macs and limit to PCs only?

PROBLEM 3

Websites blocked

Could we have a way of predicting when the permissions are to expire and reset before lessons are disrupted.

PROBLEM 4

The hard drives of the macs are now filling restricting software upgrades and general usage.

The solution to this could be much more complicated. The problem seems to be caused by the way they have been configured to integrate into the windows based system used by the rest of the school. The mac I use in the studio has not got this problem so I suspect it is caused by data (system data) as a consequence of having multiple users in their present configuration. I would suggest looking at reconfiguring the macs and creating a seperate network for the department. There would still need to be internet for google classroom and drive but could be configured for optimum mac use.



There have of course been school wide internet issues this week that have added to the problems but hopefully these are now fixed.

Unfortunately I am not a network specialist and don't have access to the software etc to solve these problems but happy to discuss and help Rachid and Vital where I can

Dave

Using IT in our music lessons is becoming untenable.

wrote:

> Hello All
>
> I'll do my best to clarify the problems that exist with the M1 music
> computers. All of the issues have been highlighted for some time (over two
> years) right back to when Kevin was out IT tech in school. Unfortunately
> the lack of a consistent tech has not helped, but Rachid is aware of them
> and seeking solutions.
>
> *PROBLEM 1*
>
> There is a problem with some Macs connecting to the network on the far
> wall in particular. Both Holly and now Rachid have highlighted the problem
> could be with the old network switches they are connected to.
>
> Solution: test and potentially upgrade the switches for L40 and test the
> individual connections.
>
> *PROBLEM 2*
>
> Password reset. The Macs seem to request user password changes much more
> often than other computers in school. On top of this there seems to be some
> synchronization issues when changing.
>
> Change the password reset settings potentially avoiding requests on the
> macs and limit to PCs only?
>
> *PROBLEM 3*
>
> Websites blocked
>
> Could we have a way of predicting when the permissions are to expire and
> reset before lessons are disrupted.
>
> *PROBLEM 4*
>
> The hard drives of the macs are now filling restricting software upgrades
> and general usage.
>
> The solution to this could be much more complicated. The problem seems to
> be caused by the way they have been configured to integrate into the
> windows based system used by the rest of the school. The mac I use in the
> studio has not got this problem so I suspect it is caused by data (system
> data) as a consequence of having multiple users in their present
> configuration. I would suggest looking at reconfiguring the macs and
> creating a seperate network for the department. There would still need to
> be internet for google classroom and drive but could be configured for
> optimum mac use.
>
>
>
> There have of course been school wide internet issues this week that have
> added to the problems but hopefully these are now fixed.
>
> Unfortunately I am not a network specialist and don't have access to the
> software etc to solve these problems but happy to discuss and help Rachid
> and Vital where I can
>
> Dave
>
>
>

[required] Title: Re: Ongoing IT issues in Music
Description:
Morning everyone -

Just providing an update - all websites are still blocked for students in
L40 on all computers. Putting the long-standing problems aside, when can we
expect to be able to access the internet in this classroom please?

Thanks
Zoe

On Wed, 24 Apr 2024 at 14:02, David Clements <dclements1@ahs.pmat.academy>
wrote:

> Hello All
>
> I'll do my best to clarify the problems that exist with the M1 music
> computers. All of the issues have been highlighted for some time (over two
> years) right back to when Kevin was out IT tech in school. Unfortunately
> the lack of a consistent tech has not helped, but Rachid is aware of them
> and seeking solutions.
>
> *PROBLEM 1*
>
> There is a problem with some Macs connecting to the network on the far
> wall in particular. Both Holly and now Rachid have highlighted the problem
> could be with the old network switches they are connected to.
>
> Solution: test and potentially upgrade the switches for L40 and test the
> individual connections.
>
> *PROBLEM 2*
>
> Password reset. The Macs seem to request user password changes much more
> often than other computers in school. On top of this there seems to be some
> synchronization issues when changing.
>
> Change the password reset settings potentially avoiding requests on the
> macs and limit to PCs only?
>
> *PROBLEM 3*
>
> Websites blocked
>
> Could we have a way of predicting when the permissions are to expire and
> reset before lessons are disrupted.
>
> *PROBLEM 4*
>
> The hard drives of the macs are now filling restricting software upgrades
> and general usage.
>
> The solution to this could be much more complicated. The problem seems to
> be caused by the way they have been configured to integrate into the
> windows based system used by the rest of the school. The mac I use in the
> studio has not got this problem so I suspect it is caused by data (system
> data) as a consequence of having multiple users in their present
> configuration. I would suggest looking at reconfiguring the macs and
> creating a seperate network for the department. There would still need to
> be internet for google classroom and drive but could be configured for
> optimum mac use.
>
>
>
> There have of course been school wide internet issues this week that have
> added to the problems but hopefully these are now fixed.
>
> Unfortunately I am not a network specialist and don't have access to the
> software etc to solve these problems but happy to discuss and help Rachid
> and Vital where I can
>
> Dave
>
>
>

Description:
Morning

Thanks
Lesley

---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: FFT Education <support@fft.org.uk>
Date: Fri, 26 Apr 2024 at 13:08
Subject: Your FFT Data Exchange connection - Immediate action required
To: <l.welsh@gps.hlt.academy>


Your FFT Data Exchange connection - Immediate action required
------------------------------

Dear Lesley

Further to our email below sent on Wednesday 17th April please be aware the
deadline for the migration of your FFT data exchange connection to
Wonde is *Tuesday
30th April*.

Immediate action is now required otherwise your data exchange connection
may be *temporarily suspended* by FFT.

Making this change is quick and easy as your school already connects with
Wonde. Log in to your Wonde portal and click on the FFT Data Exchange tile.
Review the requested permissions and if you are happy, simply click
'Approve'.

If you have done this in the last two days please ignore this email.
*Log in to Wonde ➜*
<https://www2.fft.org.uk/e/866372/2024-04-26/7sy1yq/995928753/h/0l8hnLSWCJLwXgCj0f08naqGf2aNOCV3-Pr3l-h2k2w>

Please refer to the email that you will have received from Wonde on
Thursday 18th April for more information.

If you have any concerns please let us know.
------------------------------
You may be aware that your school uses *Groupcall *to connect your
Management Information System (MIS) to *FFT's Data Exchange*. Data Exchange
is a free service that ensures the information we have for your students
reflects their most current details.

As part of improving our services to schools, we will soon transition your
FFT Data Exchange connection *from Groupcall to Wonde*. You will shortly
receive an email from our Wonde partners requesting you to authorise or
onboard your connection with Wonde.Please action this email. *Your
connection with Groupcall will be removed by 30th April 2024.*

If you prefer to keep your FFT Data Exchange connection with Groupcall,
please reply to this email, stating your reason for wanting to remain with
Groupcall. We will then review your request and follow up with you to
discuss further.

We appreciate your continued support and look forward to ensuring a smooth
transition to Wonde.

Yours sincerely,


*Helen Robinson*

*Customer and Operations Director FFT Education*

The Whole Trust Training Day will take place on Monday 2nd September 2024
at the York Barbican and all staff members are invited to attend the
event.  The event runs from 9.30am-1.30pm and all staff who normally work
these hours should attend.  Those staff who do not work these hours are
invited but attendance is optional.  However, you would be expected to use
your hours to complete any annual statutory training. For those who cannot
attend a video of the main speakers will be available post event.
Please complete the form to confirm your attendance.

Description:
Hello Hope Sentamu Team,
 
 We are contacting you again, as the same virus was detected again on the same host, for username "HLT\l.henderson" - the file was quarantined by CrowdStrike.
 Can you please confirm if this host - "GRA-AR2-TPC", is a multipurpose host? Also, by any chance, are the user inserting the SD cards/USB devices into their personal machines, perhaps for homework purposes?
 
 In your environment, are there any hosts NOT protected by CrowdStrike, which might be used by the users and lead to the propagation of this executable? 
 Moreover, we are seeing that this hostname is currently vulnerable to several CVEs out there. Could you please ensure it's being patched against the most critical and high severity ones, in order to reduce the attack surface. 
 Kind regards

Hi James

Quite a simple idea for this - the only question is which staff will manage it/police it.

They'd like an email address creating for people to send photos to for use in the Y11 leaving assembly and prom.

I mentioned the possibility of spam etc. but all the more reason for a member of staff to have access too. I'm assuming a password will be set up (by you would be good, so that there isn't confusion) and then staff/Harry and Isabelle (Y11 students) can collect useable photos from the account.

Obviously, anyone sending inappropriate photos to the email should be easy to identify. Perhaps a block on external email addresses able to send mail to this address too if possible? That would prevent anyone going to the trouble of emailing from anonymous addresses.

I think that's all I can think of, in terms of potential issues.

Seeing as they are in my form, I'd be fine to help H and I manage this/police it for them unless HoY Claire Hadcroft would rather look after this?

Ian

We wanted to inform you about an important update regarding the transition
from Mobility Print Chrome Apps to Extensions.



Google has deprecated Chrome Apps and now requires all apps to be replaced
with extensions. Consequently, PaperCut Mobility Print Chrome App will
transition to an Extension starting April 16, 2024.



If your organization currently uses the Mobility Print Chrome App on
Windows, macOS, or Linux, you must migrate to the new Mobility Print
Extension before June 30, 2024.



Similarly, if you use the Mobility Print Chrome App solely on ChromeOS, you
must migrate before August 30, 2024.

Description:
Hi Hope Sentamy Learning Trust, 
 CrowdStrike detected the execution of a potentially malicious file. The process has been terminated and the file is quarantined.
 
 Classification: A file written to the file system meets the on-sensor machine learning high confidence threshold for malicious files. Detection is based on a high degree of entropy, packing, anti-malware evasion, or other similarity to known malware.
 Date/Time: Apr. 16, 2024 09:31:48 local time, (2024-04-16 13:31:48 UTC) Host: ASA-SD-102-08 IP: 87.102.62.19 User: HLT\22asa-da21 Filename: Auto Clicker.exe File Type: executable File Path: \Device\HarddiskVolume4\Users\22asa-da21\AppData\Local\Temp\979f5fc2-72d4-4552-b4c2-90b11e5acda3_Auto Clicker.zip.da3\Auto Clicker.exe SHA256: 5779777a3b945db41a30179677d9e394a499875ce52c8c8cc8491c454646c132
 
 Our research shows that the file that is being executed belongs to an application that several of our security vendors have flagged as PUP as the application performs changes to the behaviour of the host without the user's knowledge, the application is an auto clicker that mimics the clicking of physical mouses used for gaming and other none essential activities, due to this we do not recommed the use of it in your environment. As mentioned before Crowdstrike quarantined the file and terminated the process but to prevent persistence on the host we recommend doing a manual deletion of the files on the containing folder. 
 Remediations
 -Manual deletion of the containing folder to prevent persistence on the host. 
 File Path: \Device\HarddiskVolume4\Users\22asa-da21\AppData\Local\Temp\979f5fc2-72d4-4552-b4c2-90b11e5acda3_Auto
 
 
 Please let us know if there is anything else we can further assist you with. Best Regards.

In schools it’s not uncommon for instances of personality clashes,
communication failings, relationship breakdowns or even bullying to develop
between staff members.



Unfortunately, these circumstances often amount to an employee submitting a
grievance against the other, which may not facilitate the desired outcome
for either party.



This is where mediation can work wonders.



During the session we will be looking at:

   - Why grievances were never intended to resolve disputes between
   colleagues (and therefore why they simply don’t work)
   - How mediation can be used as a better solution to these problems
   - Why mediation is the most cost effective and successful approach in
   the long run.

You'll be surrounded by your peers in the *Judicium*
<https://d37kk204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/2O+113/d37kk204/VWfMvR3fNrMkW1zhZBl2pP890W6klx535cZmSQN4vJDLM3hKBbW7Y8-PT6lZ3l2V2YbTg5Wt_gvW6MpjXX1HWZKmW2YPnMm5rnjNHW6bwK967rp06XW8MwMny7PW1RBW2dqfFW2b-p0fW3rYKNq6_mpQfW3gx3Sx8FtvgPW19W_Wb66Vy3PW6jcKvk72FP2FV5RbkX7zDkXwW1LBS6h95ngrtW10YRzz6SJvP2N2Kg2ZSB5ZSTV3b0Lc1GQG5zN4tvxmpNYyJcW81_5dC8cQj-CW2809lh45RgBFVZK1Pm9hFvFwW5y_4kl8gqb5SW4hzPsq4LQZFgW3WF1Y44_MjTwW8z95Bt8HbpVxV2STxJ6zJg3hW1vKlPf3qh5yNW9gbB1P5DCzJZf7nw7fz04>

drawn from a multitude of school-settings. At Judicium, we believe in
open-collaboration, networking and *peer-to-peer support.*

We welcome your questions, so please email any beforehand and we'll try to
answer these live 'on the sofa'.

Can't make the session? We understand how busy your school day is. However,
if you would like to receive the follow up material which covers everything
discussed during the live sofa session, simply register for either session
time. The summary notes will be sent to your inbox the same day.

Stay safe, stay well. And let's all stay kind.

Best Wishes,
Ashley

[required] Title: Ticket to request Sibelius check outs
Description:
please can you contact Academia and ask them to open up the ability for me
to check-out our Sibelius licenses. I always could do this our previous
workstation set up but it's been disabled on our systems. (i.e. I've never
been able to do it on the new systems). To give a bit of insight - the
Sibelius software requires my machine (my teacher's mac) to be logged in
and have static IP addresses for the software to function straight away on
student machines. If I'm not in the room (for example there's a cover
lesson), the software cannot be used and the students lose coursework time.
By checking out the licenses I can still control the licenses - who has
them and for how long, and there's a maximum 365 days check out period,
which is most helpful for me to do in July - our quietest time. Checked out
licenses don't need the teacher's mac to be on. The other issue I'm having
is because the IP addresses are not static, every time it changes I have to
enter the Administrator username and password on each student computer. The
bottom line is, if I can be allowed to 'check-out' the licenses to our
student mac workstations nothing of the above will be a problem and the
software will work for them first time, every time. As I'm only checking
out licenses to computers in the same room I can't see why there would be a
problem with this.

Cheers
We are in J08 if you can come this lesson - thanks.
Amelia

[required] Title: Fwd: Elevate Your Teaching & Learning with Education Technology
Description:
Good morning,

Would you be able to tell me who currently receives these kind of general
update/newsletter style emails?
These could be really useful to some groups of staff in our schools so we'd
like to review who is receiving them please.

Many thanks,
Mia

On Tue, 9 Apr 2024 at 12:00, Vital York Limited <training@vitalyork.com>
wrote:

> Explore our 'quick-read' newsletter filled with #edtech tips and info to
> help enhance teaching and learning
> View this email in your browser
> <https://mailchi.mp/9262b282acbe/elevate-your-teaching-learning-with-education-technology?e=19dac1315a>
>
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=45bdf4816d&e=19dac1315a>
>
> T&L Summer #1 2024
>
>
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=1851bcda33&e=19dac1315a>
> *Hi, and welcome to the first Vital Teaching & Learning newsletter!*
>
> This newsletter, which will come out at the beginning of each half term,
> summarises some of the latest developments in educational technology. We
> know teachers are busy so it is designed to be a quick read!
>
> We hope you find it informative - please let us know if there is anything
> you would like us to feature.
>
> *Richard & Charlotte*
> Education Technology Consultants | Vital York Limited
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=99ada91c3d&e=19dac1315a>
> *Bett Show 2024*
>
> Bett Show 2024 once again showcased the best of education technology from
> around the world, with this year's spotlight firmly on AI (which we will
> explore more below!). This was commented on by the Education Secretary at
> the Bett Show opening address, and only last week, Parliament approved the
> world’s first *Artificial Intelligence Act*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=3f234dff0f&e=19dac1315a>
> .
>
> *Our takeaways from Bett *
> At the *Canva*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=9624df0887&e=19dac1315a>
> stand, we were given a showcase on how to create animations whilst also
> using their fantastic - and free - Magic Media app. This generates text to
> image using AI and we explored this at the Vital ETC back in October. It
> can be found under the ‘Apps’ section when creating a design. If you
> haven’t used it yet, Canva is an effective graphic design tool you and your
> students can use in the classroom to support your teaching of the
> Information Technology computing strand.
>
> Micro:bits have become an essential tool for coding in schools, supported
> over the last year by Nominet's initiative to distribute them to UK primary
> schools for free. We hope you have got yours! Whilst at the *Kitronik*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=99511b81c8&e=19dac1315a>
> stand, we were told about a range of new accessories coming out for the
> *Micro:bit*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=04c18b24df&e=19dac1315a>,
> so to those looking to extend their coding skills further, keep an eye out
> for these!
>
> Amidst the big names, startups like *MyWordPal*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=7f0815cfb9&e=19dac1315a>
> caught our eye. Their reading programme, tailored for dyslexic and
> struggling readers, employs AI-driven voice recognition to provide
> personalised support, and we can see this programme being useful for
> schools and worth checking out (although they are currently updating their
> *website*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=ca786592cc&e=19dac1315a>,
> you can find them on *facebook*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=e45f6d497d&e=19dac1315a>
> and *LinkedIn*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=8f7d48a6b7&e=19dac1315a>
> !)
>
>
> Artificial Intelligence is here to stay and will be a valuable tool and
> resource to support those working within education.
>
> We know of schools already harnessing AI by using paid tools specifically
> designed for use within education such as *Mr P's TeachMateAI*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=a4c3baafda&e=19dac1315a>,
> *LessonLab*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=c461803bee&e=19dac1315a>
> or *Magic School*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=40e944bf3e&e=19dac1315a>.
> These are great resources to support teachers with workload although they
> lack the generative capabilities which can be useful when wanting to
> develop responses. Google's recently launched *Gemini*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=7a8643dd9c&e=19dac1315a>
> (formerly Bard) AI tool offers this generative capability so you can ask it
> to edit and improve the responses given. However, we can't forget the
> original, *ChatGPT*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=5f6a9aa4f5&e=19dac1315a>.
> At only 16 months old, this is the one that started at it all. The current
> free 3.5 version still remains a valuable tool on offer to use.
>
> *Twilight training session - COMING SOON!*
> Keep your eyes peeled for details of our upcoming twilight training
> session, focusing on AI in Education, which we will be hosting later this
> term. Details to follow.....
>
>
> *Check out this fun resource
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=1de3b24eb1&e=19dac1315a>*
>
> *What is it?*
> *Neal.fun*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=9c3134c100&e=19dac1315a>
> is an Aladdin’s cave of a website that gives teachers access to lots of
> other interesting resources!
>
> *How might I use it?*
> Key Stage 2 children will enjoy exploring it themselves but many of the
> tools are perfect for teaching across the curriculum. Explore the size of
> objects in space or look at what sea creatures can be found at different
> depths!
>
> *Where can I find it?*
> You can click on the link above and we have also added it to our
> *Symbaloo*
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=987da262ff&e=19dac1315a>
> (which should now be available within your Vital Bookmarks).
>
> *Need support or training?*
>
> Is there anything in this newsletter you think would benefit your school?
> Please get in touch for more info or if you need support in developing
> computing / education technology use across your school.
>
>    - *Richard Skidmore*
>    E: *r.skidmore@vitalyork.com* <r.skidmore@vitalyork.com>
>    (Mon/Tue)
>    - *Charlotte Platts*
>    E: *c.platts@vitalyork.com*
>    <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=6da34e9390&e=19dac1315a>
>    (Thu/Fri)
>
>
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=aa33783642&e=19dac1315a>
> [image: Twitter]
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=91c5d30b9b&e=19dac1315a>
> [image: LinkedIn]
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=74bea8bf3f&e=19dac1315a>
> [image: Website]
> <https://vitalyork.us14.list-manage.com/track/click?u=93f537103a764aa5898210075&id=955d26c6cd&e=19dac1315a>
> *Our mailing address is:*
> Vital York Limited
> 480 Huntington Road
> York
> YO32 9PX

[required] Title: Ladybird / Visulaiser Software Installation Request for Hall Laptop
Description:
Hi there,

In the second week of this half term, the head of English for the Trust,
Matt O'Neil, will be delivering a Walking Talking Mock to our entire Year
10 cohort in the hall.

For this to be possible, the laptop in the hall will need to be installed
with the Ladybird / visualiser software as the Walking Talking Mock is not
possible without this.

Would you be able to set this up for us during this week so that we can
ensure it is in place for Monday 15th April when the WTM will take place?
We will also need to check whether we have any available visualisers (we
have them in the English department / classrooms, but it may be necessary
to order a new visualizer for the purpose of this WTM).

If you could let me know whether the above will be possible and when it
might be completed, that would be great.

Thank you in advance,

Adam Metcalfe

________________________________
From: Distribution <Distribution@parentpay.com>
Sent: 27 March 2024 12:07
To: C Carr <c.carr@huntington-ed.org.uk>
Subject: Photo Batch Import Licence 2024/25 - Huntington School - 8164063


Dear colleague,



Please find attached your Photo Importer licence files along with instructions on how to apply. Your new licence is valid until 31st March 2025. Please keep this email safe so that your licence is available when you require it.



What do I need to do now?

Do not attempt to open the licence file other than by using the batch import process within SIMS.net. You just need to right click on the Photo Licence file attached to this email and save it somewhere to your system.



How do I order a new licence once this one expires?

Each year you will be required to log into the ESS Portal to administer your agreement with ESS, and Photo Import Licence will be included in this, once your initial term for Photo Import Licence expires. This means that your Photo Import Licence will automatically renew and each year we will issue you with an updated Photo Import Licence automatically.



What if I wish to cancel my Photo Import licence?



We require at least 90 days written notice, prior to your next renewal date (31st March) in order to cancel your Photo Import licence. This means that notice is always due, no later than the 31st December prior to your initial contract term end date (for example, if your contract term end date is 31st March 2025, then notice is required no later than 31st December 2024). Notice must be sent, in writing to SIMSContracts@parentpay.com<mailto:SIMSContracts@parentpay.com>. If sufficient notice is not received, then your Photo Importer Licence will be automatically renewed, as per the Terms outlined in the ESS Portal when this becomes available to you.



Who should I contact for support?

Distribution are unable to provide technical support; if you require support, please contact our Service Desk on:-



T: 03330 150 212

E: support@educationsoftwaresolutions.co.uk<mailto:support@educationsoftwaresolutions.co.uk>

To: Vital York Support <help@vitalyork.com>

Good morning,

I'm not logging an immediate issue but flagging up something for after May half-term in terms of hardware requirements.

Every year, in the last half-term, year 9 students in English have to present a speech to the class. This is part of their GCSE. We have to film these to send to the exam board to check our marking. Historically we have used the ipads that were in the English/Media department but I understand these have been decommissioned. Was there any plan to replace them? If not, have you got any thoughts on the best way to film the speeches this year?

Essentially, all English teachers with a year 9 group need a device. That means about 8 or 9 devices. They need that device every time they teach a year 9 lesson for about 2-3 weeks. It doesn't feel like booking the Chromebook trollies would work because the devices would need to be returned straight away and so anything filmed in the previous lesson would still be on there and that feels problematic. Plus the same teacher would need the same device back so all recordings from one class can be kept and then downloaded into the same place.

I'd be keen to talk through options are some point before Easter because even though it feels a while away, I'd like a plan in place well ahead of May half-term.

Many thanks

Marcus
